  "datePublished": "2026-01-01",
  "description": "Tabletop role-playing games emerged in the early 1970s from the overlap of miniatures wargaming, fantasy fandom, and referee-led hobby play. Early Dungeons \u0026amp; Dragons made that synthesis durable: it combined campaign play, character-centered decision-making, and a referee who could interpret or change rules as needed. For a sourced overview of that formation, see Tabletop Role-Playing Games.\nThe first phase of TTRPG history is best understood as hobby consolidation. Conventions, hobby shops, club play, and zines gave the form places to circulate. Designers quickly built alternatives to D\u0026amp;D, but they usually inherited the same basic table structure: players controlled characters, a referee managed the world, and the rules operated as a flexible framework rather than as closed code.\n",
